1
00:00:00,959 --> 00:00:09,468
[SPEAKER_08]: Hello, everybody, and welcome to the December 2023 Human Rights Commission meeting with the City of Medford.

2
00:00:10,108 --> 00:00:14,553
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm Frances Marchand, Director of Diversity, Equity and Inclusion.

3
00:00:14,573 --> 00:00:21,860
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm now going to popcorn it over on to our commissioners.

4
00:00:21,880 --> 00:00:23,542
[SPEAKER_08]: So over to you, Diane.

5
00:00:25,633 --> 00:00:27,494
[SPEAKER_00]: Hi, I'm Diane McDonald.

6
00:00:28,474 --> 00:00:32,535
[SPEAKER_00]: I've been on the commission for the last year and I'm a resident of West Medford.

7
00:00:32,935 --> 00:00:40,957
[SPEAKER_00]: And then I also work in higher ed as a community builder through stories and I'm a tour guide at Royal House and Slave Quarters locally.

8
00:00:40,977 --> 00:00:45,099
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Diane.

9
00:00:45,159 --> 00:00:47,399
[SPEAKER_08]: Would you like to popcorn it over to someone else?

10
00:00:47,419 --> 00:00:49,860
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, I'll popcorn over to Stephanie.

11
00:00:51,995 --> 00:00:53,756
[SPEAKER_09]: Hi everyone, Stephanie Cornell.

12
00:00:54,056 --> 00:01:03,562
[SPEAKER_09]: I have been first year on the commission and I am a Medford resident as well and I will popcorn it to Maureen.

13
00:01:03,582 --> 00:01:05,824
[SPEAKER_07]: Hi, I'm Maureen Curley.

14
00:01:05,844 --> 00:01:08,645
[SPEAKER_07]: I am, I also live in West Medford.

15
00:01:08,905 --> 00:01:10,406
[SPEAKER_07]: I've been on, this is my third meeting.

16
00:01:10,426 --> 00:01:19,312
[SPEAKER_07]: I am also a volunteer here at the Royal House and Slave Quarters and I will send it over to Jack.

17
00:01:20,787 --> 00:01:22,108
[SPEAKER_11]: Hi, everyone, Chief Jack Buckley.

18
00:01:22,488 --> 00:01:26,671
[SPEAKER_11]: I've been a police officer in the city of Medford for 25 plus years.

19
00:01:26,812 --> 00:01:31,795
[SPEAKER_11]: I am just starting my sixth year of Chief of Police in my sixth year on the Human Rights Commission.

20
00:01:31,855 --> 00:01:32,716
[SPEAKER_11]: So welcome, everyone.

21
00:01:36,899 --> 00:01:39,281
[SPEAKER_11]: And I will send it to Rob, I think, right?

22
00:01:41,263 --> 00:01:41,923
[SPEAKER_01]: Thanks, Chief.

23
00:01:41,983 --> 00:01:43,164
[SPEAKER_01]: Yep, this is Rob Klein.

24
00:01:43,184 --> 00:01:47,027
[SPEAKER_01]: I've been on the commission about three years at this point.

25
00:01:48,446 --> 00:01:51,796
[SPEAKER_01]: Happy, lucky resident of South Medford.

26
00:01:55,579 --> 00:01:59,443
[SPEAKER_01]: And my professional endeavors don't align with the board whatsoever.

27
00:01:59,503 --> 00:02:02,045
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm in tech sales for reference.

28
00:02:03,146 --> 00:02:05,988
[SPEAKER_01]: I think we do have a new face on the call as well, Adam.

29
00:02:06,008 --> 00:02:11,633
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't know, Frances, if this is the opportunity to do an added intro or we should hold there.

30
00:02:11,653 --> 00:02:19,720
[SPEAKER_08]: We should hold there for now because we're going to go into the intro right after our touchstones.

31
00:02:23,427 --> 00:02:30,169
[SPEAKER_08]: All right, do I have a commissioner volunteering to read our HRC meeting touchstones?

32
00:02:35,350 --> 00:02:37,831
[SPEAKER_08]: Make me be the reader of the touchstones.

33
00:02:37,951 --> 00:02:45,293
[SPEAKER_11]: I don't have a problem reading it, Frances, I just don't have it up.

34
00:02:45,313 --> 00:02:46,314
[SPEAKER_11]: Can you put it on the screen?

35
00:02:46,474 --> 00:02:48,214
[SPEAKER_11]: I just don't have it in front of me.

36
00:02:48,234 --> 00:02:49,895
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay, all righty, hold on.

37
00:02:51,763 --> 00:02:54,385
[SPEAKER_08]: I usually prepare better, you know that.

38
00:02:54,566 --> 00:02:56,067
[SPEAKER_08]: Right, let me look for it.

39
00:02:56,507 --> 00:02:57,128
[SPEAKER_08]: Bring it up.

40
00:02:59,390 --> 00:03:00,011
[SPEAKER_08]: It's there.

41
00:03:24,177 --> 00:03:27,189
[SPEAKER_08]: Of course, I can't find it handily.

42
00:03:27,892 --> 00:03:28,354
[SPEAKER_08]: Here we go.

43
00:03:47,772 --> 00:03:49,920
[SPEAKER_11]: Method Human Rights Commission meeting touchstones.

44
00:03:50,683 --> 00:03:53,934
[SPEAKER_11]: Be present, presume welcome, and extend welcome.

45
00:03:55,807 --> 00:04:00,268
[SPEAKER_11]: Order of meeting is the commission meets to discuss the agenda first.

46
00:04:00,888 --> 00:04:05,249
[SPEAKER_11]: At conclusion of meeting agenda, members of the public are invited to share comments.

47
00:04:05,930 --> 00:04:09,190
[SPEAKER_11]: Raise your hand before speaking and avoid interrupting others.

48
00:04:10,031 --> 00:04:14,092
[SPEAKER_11]: Speak for yourself and speak your truth in ways that respect others' truths.

49
00:04:15,032 --> 00:04:18,473
[SPEAKER_11]: Acknowledge others' lived experience to promote human dignity.

50
00:04:19,517 --> 00:04:20,237
[SPEAKER_11]: Listen deeply.

51
00:04:20,918 --> 00:04:25,600
[SPEAKER_11]: Believe that it's possible to emerge refreshed, surprised, and less burdened.

52
00:04:26,321 --> 00:04:29,442
[SPEAKER_11]: Expect and accept a lack of closure.

53
00:04:30,083 --> 00:04:32,624
[SPEAKER_11]: When things get difficult, turn to WANDA.

54
00:04:35,085 --> 00:04:36,106
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Chief.

55
00:04:37,626 --> 00:04:48,172
[SPEAKER_08]: It's really incredible that at this time I have to say the seconds to last and the last bullet are just so real right now.

56
00:04:49,970 --> 00:05:01,128
[SPEAKER_08]: expect and accept a little closure and when things get difficult tend to wonder when you look at just what is occurring on a global scale.

57
00:05:03,304 --> 00:05:23,130
[SPEAKER_08]: All right, at this time, we're going to reverse our typical agenda, because we have Adam LaFrance joining us on behalf of the Massachusetts Human Rights Coalition as our invited guest.

58
00:05:23,250 --> 00:05:29,952
[SPEAKER_08]: So I'm going to turn it over to Adam to provide

59
00:05:32,133 --> 00:05:37,216
[SPEAKER_08]: to provide update, introduction.

60
00:05:37,756 --> 00:05:46,621
[SPEAKER_08]: And then when Adam is done, it will go back to commissioners to ask questions and stuff.

61
00:05:47,202 --> 00:05:48,643
[SPEAKER_08]: So over to you, Adam.

62
00:05:48,663 --> 00:05:48,703
[SPEAKER_08]: Hi.

63
00:05:49,763 --> 00:05:51,024
[SPEAKER_05]: Good evening, everyone.

64
00:05:51,204 --> 00:05:52,565
[SPEAKER_05]: And thank you for inviting me, Frances.

65
00:05:52,645 --> 00:05:55,267
[SPEAKER_05]: It's really nice to join you this evening.

66
00:05:57,055 --> 00:06:00,958
[SPEAKER_05]: and just talk through a little bit about what the coalition is.

67
00:06:02,300 --> 00:06:03,040
[SPEAKER_05]: And hello to Munir.

68
00:06:03,180 --> 00:06:03,861
[SPEAKER_05]: Nice to see you again.

69
00:06:05,342 --> 00:06:12,027
[SPEAKER_05]: We've worked in the past through this organization, which I have to say wouldn't exist without the efforts of Medford.

70
00:06:12,447 --> 00:06:19,893
[SPEAKER_05]: It started in Medford with the former diversity director, Diane McLeod, who retired about 2015, 2014, 2016, right around there.

71
00:06:23,830 --> 00:06:25,531
[SPEAKER_05]: And it was something that she had created.

72
00:06:25,551 --> 00:06:35,614
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm not sure if it was just her or in partnership with someone else, but my recollection is it's her sometime in the mid 1990s.

73
00:06:35,814 --> 00:06:42,996
[SPEAKER_05]: And it worked to build this association of

74
00:06:43,847 --> 00:07:06,421
[SPEAKER_05]: others who are parts of human rights commissions in other towns in and around the Commonwealth to come together and trade notes and exchange stories, troubleshoot issues, and see how each of us could do our work in our towns that much better, and have others we could turn to with those questions or issues.

75
00:07:06,801 --> 00:07:11,984
[SPEAKER_05]: And that's actually how I came to be part of it, through the Melrose Human Rights Commission,

76
00:07:13,746 --> 00:07:19,069
[SPEAKER_05]: which I joined in 2013 and was on for six years before term limits.

77
00:07:20,150 --> 00:07:21,410
[SPEAKER_05]: And I finished my term.

78
00:07:22,731 --> 00:07:25,973
[SPEAKER_05]: But through that, came to participate in this group.

79
00:07:26,794 --> 00:07:29,816
[SPEAKER_05]: And when Diane retired, several of us said, well, let's keep this group going.

80
00:07:29,856 --> 00:07:32,877
[SPEAKER_05]: We really benefited from this.

81
00:07:32,897 --> 00:07:33,698
[SPEAKER_05]: We really like this.

82
00:07:33,818 --> 00:07:38,561
[SPEAKER_05]: And it's been immensely helpful, especially as some of us came into it without maybe some

83
00:07:39,618 --> 00:07:47,722
[SPEAKER_05]: uh, you know, experience in this kind of work, but really a commitment to advancing this kind of work, um, and seeing it happen, uh, at the local level.

84
00:07:48,402 --> 00:07:51,383
[SPEAKER_05]: And, uh, you know, so an opportunity to learn a fair amount.

85
00:07:52,424 --> 00:07:58,486
[SPEAKER_05]: Um, so we kept the, the traditions, uh, that Diane had established.

86
00:07:58,526 --> 00:08:02,568
[SPEAKER_05]: We meet the second Friday of every month, uh, at 9 AM.

87
00:08:03,867 --> 00:08:05,167
[SPEAKER_05]: And that's for about two hours.

88
00:08:06,068 --> 00:08:09,948
[SPEAKER_05]: We do that almost every month, except for a couple months in the summertime.

89
00:08:10,148 --> 00:08:12,109
[SPEAKER_05]: So fairly tied to the academic calendar.

90
00:08:14,689 --> 00:08:27,812
[SPEAKER_05]: And actually, one of the silver linings of the COVID remote virtual experience was really being able to expand participation across the Commonwealth.

91
00:08:28,899 --> 00:08:34,940
[SPEAKER_05]: So where before we would meet in person at Medford City Hall, upstairs, we now meet by Zoom.

92
00:08:35,881 --> 00:08:43,802
[SPEAKER_05]: And consequently, we have many more people from all across the Commonwealth who will attend and some outside the Commonwealth.

93
00:08:44,342 --> 00:08:48,163
[SPEAKER_05]: We have a couple of representatives from Rhode Island who now join us.

94
00:08:48,903 --> 00:08:56,905
[SPEAKER_05]: And there's been other folks who are interested, who maybe don't have something like this in their state, but said this is something we'd like to, you know,

95
00:08:57,518 --> 00:09:00,600
[SPEAKER_05]: can we participate and see what we can do and bring back to our communities?

96
00:09:05,162 --> 00:09:07,103
[SPEAKER_05]: So essentially, that's what we do once a month.

97
00:09:07,343 --> 00:09:15,027
[SPEAKER_05]: And we probably have, everyone's fairly busy, but I think we usually have between 10 and 20 participants each month.

98
00:09:15,948 --> 00:09:19,429
[SPEAKER_05]: But we probably have, we have well over 100 people who are part of our

99
00:09:21,963 --> 00:09:23,043
[SPEAKER_05]: our communication group.

100
00:09:24,344 --> 00:09:27,466
[SPEAKER_05]: So we can not only talk in meetings, we can talk online.

101
00:09:28,167 --> 00:09:31,909
[SPEAKER_05]: We have essentially a listserv or a Google group where that can happen.

102
00:09:33,770 --> 00:09:38,113
[SPEAKER_05]: If things happen in between meetings, our conversations last longer than those meetings.

103
00:09:38,433 --> 00:09:39,674
[SPEAKER_05]: So it's been a really great resource.

104
00:09:41,165 --> 00:09:53,347
[SPEAKER_05]: And in addition to our monthly meetings, we have started in the last few years trying to have annual or semi-annual convenings that focus on a particular topic each time.

105
00:09:54,487 --> 00:10:08,510
[SPEAKER_05]: And those are essentially a half day or three quarter day in-person networking event where we have guest speakers and really delve into a topic and

106
00:10:09,406 --> 00:10:24,095
[SPEAKER_05]: try to understand it a little bit better, and see what we can do in our respective communities at that local level to either raise awareness or advance or support one issue or another related to that topic.

107
00:10:24,715 --> 00:10:37,363
[SPEAKER_05]: So in May, we just had that on the topic of health and health care equity in the Commonwealth, in part looking at the health equity compact and the legislation that's currently pending at the statehouse.

108
00:10:39,478 --> 00:10:42,499
[SPEAKER_05]: and some of the serious issues around that here in the Commonwealth.

109
00:10:43,779 --> 00:10:46,180
[SPEAKER_05]: And we've tried to do that pretty annually.

110
00:10:48,921 --> 00:10:53,703
[SPEAKER_05]: So we're now in between and probably looking at our next topic for our next convening.

111
00:10:56,143 --> 00:11:06,087
[SPEAKER_05]: So other than our monthly meetings and our occasional convenings, in-person convenings, we also have been trying to build more of a resource bank.

112
00:11:07,764 --> 00:11:13,048
[SPEAKER_05]: but part of which is internal and members can access.

113
00:11:13,269 --> 00:11:14,830
[SPEAKER_05]: And some of it is actually on our website.

114
00:11:15,430 --> 00:11:21,916
[SPEAKER_05]: So if you're looking for representative examples of things like public statements, you can look there.

115
00:11:22,176 --> 00:11:30,483
[SPEAKER_05]: There's a section there most recently on statements that have been issued by different commissions relating to Israel and Gaza.

116
00:11:31,223 --> 00:11:32,224
[SPEAKER_05]: But there are others as well.

117
00:11:34,206 --> 00:11:35,167
[SPEAKER_05]: I just take a quick look.

118
00:11:40,430 --> 00:12:03,975
[SPEAKER_05]: They talk about a number of different things that have come up, I think, have been the most common experiences across HRCs, and that have included land acknowledgments, relationships with law enforcement, holiday cultural calendars that schools or municipalities can publish and be mindful of and respect everything that's going on.

119
00:12:06,124 --> 00:12:17,151
[SPEAKER_05]: community DEI positions, equity assessments, ways in which to structure a commission, because they differ.

120
00:12:17,792 --> 00:12:22,695
[SPEAKER_05]: Some have obligatory liaisons from different departments.

121
00:12:23,215 --> 00:12:25,777
[SPEAKER_05]: Others, like Melrose, are much more open.

122
00:12:26,578 --> 00:12:27,618
[SPEAKER_05]: So it can really depend.

123
00:12:27,638 --> 00:12:30,360
[SPEAKER_05]: Is that a question?

124
00:12:32,817 --> 00:12:35,897
[SPEAKER_05]: Which, by the way, feel free to ask any questions as they come up.

125
00:12:39,072 --> 00:12:42,055
[SPEAKER_08]: You know, thank you so much commissioners.

126
00:12:43,015 --> 00:12:50,522
[SPEAKER_08]: As I said, it was best to have Adam here because I couldn't do justice to the information provided.

127
00:12:50,682 --> 00:13:02,952
[SPEAKER_08]: And thank you for giving me the opportunity to share your email addresses because you should have already been receiving some of the communications that have gone out.

128
00:13:03,092 --> 00:13:05,794
[SPEAKER_08]: Most recent communication was in regards to

129
00:13:06,675 --> 00:13:11,118
[SPEAKER_08]: the land acknowledgments that was done.

130
00:13:11,518 --> 00:13:20,604
[SPEAKER_08]: I hope I'm not confusing it with the decision to change the seal unless I could be confusing two separate emails.

131
00:13:21,545 --> 00:13:23,346
[SPEAKER_08]: But do you have any questions for Adam?

132
00:13:23,406 --> 00:13:28,670
[SPEAKER_08]: This is a great time for commissioners to ask their questions.

133
00:13:32,512 --> 00:13:33,993
[SPEAKER_05]: There were a few notices that went out.

134
00:13:34,053 --> 00:13:34,914
[SPEAKER_05]: I think one was the,

135
00:13:36,171 --> 00:13:41,272
[SPEAKER_05]: on the work of the committee that was working to change the seal that went out recently.

136
00:13:43,032 --> 00:13:59,155
[SPEAKER_05]: There was another one on the zoning for bathrooms and plumbing that will help facilitate development and avoid having to go through special permits and such.

137
00:14:01,596 --> 00:14:03,616
[SPEAKER_08]: Commissioner McDonald, go ahead, please.

138
00:14:05,775 --> 00:14:19,097
[SPEAKER_00]: So, so we're still an incomplete commission where we're looking to fill 3 slots and I would just love to get a sense from you Adam and thank you for joining us.

139
00:14:20,497 --> 00:14:26,240
[SPEAKER_00]: What are some of the high performing, high functioning commissions in the state that you've observed?

140
00:14:27,181 --> 00:14:40,408
[SPEAKER_00]: Because I feel as if we're still trying to find our rhythm together and, you know, finish filling out the commission and really, you know, have a cohesive charge and leadership.

141
00:14:40,468 --> 00:14:41,088
[SPEAKER_00]: So we're still

142
00:14:41,708 --> 00:14:46,293
[SPEAKER_00]: We're all still working together on that, even though we have a number of initiatives on the calendar.

143
00:14:46,814 --> 00:14:52,480
[SPEAKER_00]: And we just made the Declaration of Human Rights in honor of, you know, December 10th.

144
00:14:52,640 --> 00:15:03,071
[SPEAKER_00]: But I would just love to hear some examples of, you know, high functioning commissions in the state that we can turn to, to just look at as role models.

145
00:15:06,053 --> 00:15:07,834
[SPEAKER_05]: They go through cycles.

146
00:15:07,854 --> 00:15:09,214
[SPEAKER_05]: Some of it can vary.

147
00:15:09,755 --> 00:15:22,960
[SPEAKER_05]: In some years, there can be a lot of activity and a lot of all hands on deck and a very active commission, some of which you'll see more of if they've been around for a while.

148
00:15:23,120 --> 00:15:24,600
[SPEAKER_05]: Arlington has been around for a long time.

149
00:15:24,680 --> 00:15:26,341
[SPEAKER_05]: Melrose has been around since the 90s.

150
00:15:26,981 --> 00:15:28,562
[SPEAKER_05]: Those are some of the earlier ones that I know of.

151
00:15:29,682 --> 00:15:33,204
[SPEAKER_05]: Brookline has been very strong and active for a very long time.

152
00:15:35,205 --> 00:15:42,348
[SPEAKER_05]: I imagine you'll see more of that in cities, so Cambridge, Somerville, particularly Cambridge.

153
00:15:43,849 --> 00:15:47,450
[SPEAKER_05]: Somerville has gone through some cycles, as best as I recollect.

154
00:15:48,750 --> 00:15:57,814
[SPEAKER_05]: I know Boston also was active for a time, then it went dormant for a time, and they were recently revived by Mayor Walsh.

155
00:15:58,674 --> 00:16:04,737
[SPEAKER_05]: And now they have, I think they're in their second or third year of activity under their new chair.

156
00:16:06,024 --> 00:16:07,205
[SPEAKER_05]: Um, but it can really depend.

157
00:16:07,706 --> 00:16:07,906
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

158
00:16:08,547 --> 00:16:11,290
[SPEAKER_05]: Um, I think one of the newest is, uh, Watertown.

159
00:16:11,550 --> 00:16:15,934
[SPEAKER_05]: They were just, uh, created, um, and approved in September or October.

160
00:16:15,954 --> 00:16:22,601
[SPEAKER_05]: Uh, and we helped them with that process and they have a very strong ordinance, uh, that they adopted.

161
00:16:22,621 --> 00:16:29,468
[SPEAKER_05]: Um, you know, as they took a look at other, other groups ordinances and some of the things that they should think about

162
00:16:30,247 --> 00:16:33,310
[SPEAKER_05]: In crafting that, there's some like borders really engaged on that.

163
00:16:34,611 --> 00:16:38,095
[SPEAKER_05]: So they put together a really great example of an HRC ordinance.

164
00:16:38,916 --> 00:16:39,997
[SPEAKER_00]: Oh, that's helpful.

165
00:16:40,157 --> 00:16:41,879
[SPEAKER_00]: And that's the city of Watertown?

166
00:16:42,199 --> 00:16:42,439
[SPEAKER_05]: Yes.

167
00:16:42,679 --> 00:16:42,820
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

168
00:16:44,209 --> 00:16:49,333
[SPEAKER_00]: And they got guidance from your coalition and other communities?

169
00:16:50,073 --> 00:16:51,614
[SPEAKER_05]: Yes.

170
00:16:51,654 --> 00:16:59,740
[SPEAKER_05]: Some of the members who are residents who are organizing that initiative reached out and participated in our group.

171
00:17:01,861 --> 00:17:10,948
[SPEAKER_05]: And then later after they'd really put together this strong package as they were getting toward the subcommittee discussions and the

172
00:17:12,722 --> 00:17:16,724
[SPEAKER_05]: the final votes, you know, we were asked to come and talk.

173
00:17:17,524 --> 00:17:25,369
[SPEAKER_05]: So it was great to see that that made it across the line and hopefully they're out the gate and getting things going.

174
00:17:26,210 --> 00:17:26,770
[SPEAKER_00]: That's great.

175
00:17:28,791 --> 00:17:29,411
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

176
00:17:29,932 --> 00:17:30,272
[SPEAKER_05]: Certainly.

177
00:17:34,214 --> 00:17:36,756
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you so much, Adam.

178
00:17:37,776 --> 00:17:38,657
[SPEAKER_08]: Commissioner Curley.

179
00:17:39,703 --> 00:17:40,484
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

180
00:17:41,224 --> 00:17:42,345
[SPEAKER_07]: Thanks so much for coming, Adam.

181
00:17:42,365 --> 00:17:43,186
[SPEAKER_07]: This is really helpful.

182
00:17:43,306 --> 00:17:47,790
[SPEAKER_07]: And I found the emails I've already seen from the group really enlightening.

183
00:17:47,870 --> 00:17:53,515
[SPEAKER_07]: So I think it's going to help us a great deal and be able to interact and find out what other people are doing.

184
00:17:53,916 --> 00:17:56,117
[SPEAKER_07]: I had a couple of questions about how they're structured.

185
00:17:56,137 --> 00:17:58,680
[SPEAKER_07]: First of all, how many are there in the state?

186
00:17:58,700 --> 00:18:02,063
[SPEAKER_07]: Do you have any idea about how many local commissions there are?

187
00:18:04,606 --> 00:18:09,229
[SPEAKER_05]: So a few years ago, we undertook a survey project.

188
00:18:09,849 --> 00:18:21,136
[SPEAKER_05]: And we all took segments of the state and drilled down into their public municipal information and tried to reach out where we could to make contact.

189
00:18:21,657 --> 00:18:28,741
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think we had about 30 commissions, predominantly in the eastern part of the state.

190
00:18:33,132 --> 00:18:46,824
[SPEAKER_05]: Let's see, since then, there have probably been about 10 or 15 more that have been created, so that we're getting much more activity, which really all of this started to tick up after around 2016.

191
00:18:46,944 --> 00:18:51,608
[SPEAKER_05]: Because when I joined the commission in Monroe in 2013, there wasn't

192
00:18:55,335 --> 00:18:56,796
[SPEAKER_05]: a whole lot of interest, it seemed.

193
00:18:56,816 --> 00:18:58,417
[SPEAKER_05]: There were a number of seats opened.

194
00:18:58,597 --> 00:18:59,858
[SPEAKER_05]: It was sort of a quiet commission.

195
00:18:59,878 --> 00:19:16,088
[SPEAKER_05]: They would have events and people would hear about it here and there, but it didn't have a lot of public presence in some ways, or energy behind, or rather interest in participating.

196
00:19:17,011 --> 00:19:23,116
[SPEAKER_05]: That changed we saw in those years with many more people being very interested in joining the commission.

197
00:19:23,797 --> 00:19:29,101
[SPEAKER_05]: My understanding from folks who've been doing this much longer than I have, that it has those cycles.

198
00:19:29,701 --> 00:19:30,742
[SPEAKER_05]: That can be something to be aware of.

199
00:19:32,203 --> 00:19:42,832
[SPEAKER_05]: We've seen probably about 30 commissions grow to about 45 in the last few years, or still nascent trying to put that together in their towns.

200
00:19:45,184 --> 00:19:48,126
[SPEAKER_05]: And some of them have developed regional subgroups.

201
00:19:48,586 --> 00:19:58,832
[SPEAKER_05]: The South Shore has a coalition, and they collaborate at that level to consider things that impacts each of those towns.

202
00:19:59,652 --> 00:20:10,879
[SPEAKER_05]: And they're all pretty much municipal commissions except for Cape Cod, which has a county-wide advisory body that handles all the towns on the Cape.

203
00:20:12,047 --> 00:20:16,829
[SPEAKER_05]: So that's the only county size, the county version that I'm aware of.

204
00:20:18,309 --> 00:20:25,151
[SPEAKER_05]: But since then, there have been growing interest in the central part of the state and out in the Berkshires.

205
00:20:25,671 --> 00:20:36,295
[SPEAKER_05]: So we have participants from North Adams and Pittsfield on occasion in and around the Worcester area or the Pioneer Valley.

206
00:20:38,775 --> 00:20:39,576
[SPEAKER_07]: Great.

207
00:20:39,696 --> 00:20:40,236
[SPEAKER_07]: That's helpful.

208
00:20:42,503 --> 00:20:50,306
[SPEAKER_07]: We've been struggling with getting members a little bit and we've been doing a lot of outreach recently, which I think is working, you know, I think it is good.

209
00:20:50,346 --> 00:20:58,630
[SPEAKER_07]: I didn't know whether you had any words of wisdom to share with us about how we might be able to recruit and we are, of course, looking for

210
00:20:59,830 --> 00:21:08,294
[SPEAKER_07]: diversity that represents Medford and we've tried, we've developed a little flyer, we've attended different events and we are trying to get out there.

211
00:21:08,335 --> 00:21:15,278
[SPEAKER_07]: If you got any hints for us or is there anything, maybe there's something in your resource that can tell us how to do it better.

212
00:21:15,778 --> 00:21:16,718
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, nothing magic.

213
00:21:17,038 --> 00:21:44,243
[SPEAKER_05]: That's basically how we did it in Melrose, reaching out every which way, whether it was through personal contacts, people we might know who might have an interest, but also events, publications in local media, whether it's social media or print media, a number of town-wide events or group organization events where we could attend and put up information and then slowly build it from there.

214
00:21:46,517 --> 00:21:50,718
[SPEAKER_05]: But yeah, that was essentially very much the same thing.

215
00:21:51,099 --> 00:21:55,540
[SPEAKER_05]: And that's where there are some pros and cons to how it's structured.

216
00:21:56,040 --> 00:22:09,805
[SPEAKER_05]: If it's like some towns, like Wakefield or others, where the school department has a liaison, the police department has a liaison, the library has a liaison, that starts to fill it up fairly quickly.

217
00:22:11,737 --> 00:22:15,219
[SPEAKER_05]: but in others where there aren't these official liaisons.

218
00:22:15,559 --> 00:22:21,743
[SPEAKER_05]: It can be you're sort of back to this scenario of really trying to publicize, raise awareness.

219
00:22:23,264 --> 00:22:36,672
[SPEAKER_05]: And depending on how the approval process is, you might have a situation where there's a town manager or a mayor who has appointment authority or nomination authority, and maybe they can do stuff too.

220
00:22:38,942 --> 00:22:55,827
[SPEAKER_05]: And that depends, too, on how much independence exists to sort of do that recruiting and onboarding as a commission yourself or, you know, that mayor or town manager likes to do it themselves.

221
00:22:58,048 --> 00:23:03,490
[SPEAKER_05]: And that's always relationships and what the ordinance says and probably tradition a little bit.

222
00:23:05,302 --> 00:23:22,213
[SPEAKER_07]: Is there a, are there any common activities that seem to be important or making subtraction or, you know, we're looking for also like how do we really function and what is it that we do beyond meeting and in

223
00:23:22,833 --> 00:23:36,099
[SPEAKER_07]: And I was wondering whether you had seen anything in particular that some commissions might do that have been successful, both in publicizing about equity and diversity within the town.

224
00:23:36,640 --> 00:23:39,861
[SPEAKER_07]: Let's see.

225
00:23:42,482 --> 00:23:44,984
[SPEAKER_05]: There's a bit of a transition, perhaps, for many.

226
00:23:45,064 --> 00:23:47,125
[SPEAKER_05]: Some of the older groups, for a long time,

227
00:23:49,592 --> 00:24:04,595
[SPEAKER_05]: did a lot of events around raising awareness of one thing or another, building relationships with different parts of the community, bringing in speakers or other folks to talk about one issue or another.

228
00:24:04,615 --> 00:24:13,036
[SPEAKER_05]: Those have been very popular components or types of things that a commission can do.

229
00:24:13,596 --> 00:24:16,137
[SPEAKER_05]: I think at the same time, a lot of groups which are

230
00:24:17,462 --> 00:24:22,727
[SPEAKER_05]: essentially sort of an advisory body, are looking to do more than events and event planning.

231
00:24:23,207 --> 00:24:29,453
[SPEAKER_04]: And I think people essentially figure that out in a second.

232
00:24:35,053 --> 00:24:41,779
[SPEAKER_04]: They're trying to figure out how they can take on the role.

233
00:24:42,300 --> 00:24:44,462
[SPEAKER_08]: Adam, I'm sorry.

234
00:24:44,562 --> 00:24:48,285
[SPEAKER_08]: We seem to have lost your sound for a moment there.

235
00:24:48,305 --> 00:24:48,385
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah.

236
00:24:50,227 --> 00:24:51,328
[SPEAKER_05]: Can you hear me now?

237
00:24:52,869 --> 00:24:53,130
[SPEAKER_05]: OK.

238
00:24:54,191 --> 00:24:57,033
[SPEAKER_05]: So there's nothing too clear yet about that.

239
00:24:57,213 --> 00:24:59,916
[SPEAKER_05]: I think people are still figuring out how best to do that.

240
00:25:02,411 --> 00:25:16,229
[SPEAKER_05]: And in some ways, it can be as there's a lot of room to imagine what could be, you know, probably in conversation with a town or city solicitor.

241
00:25:16,249 --> 00:25:16,309
[SPEAKER_05]: But

242
00:25:20,192 --> 00:25:24,234
[SPEAKER_05]: different boards, other boards or advisory boards as well.

243
00:25:24,274 --> 00:25:24,894
[SPEAKER_05]: What do they do?

244
00:25:25,214 --> 00:25:26,454
[SPEAKER_05]: That might be one place to look.

245
00:25:26,714 --> 00:25:31,396
[SPEAKER_05]: And that's a conversation that we've had among our members as well.

246
00:25:31,416 --> 00:25:34,777
[SPEAKER_05]: Let's take a look at what other bodies are doing, what authorities they have.

247
00:25:35,277 --> 00:25:44,981
[SPEAKER_05]: Could there be other authorities that are granted to this Human Rights Commission to review certain proposed legislation or projects or to

248
00:25:50,068 --> 00:25:56,253
[SPEAKER_05]: either be able to reach in and advise or be approached and asked to review and advise on something.

249
00:25:57,994 --> 00:26:10,744
[SPEAKER_05]: But, sorry, not much more concrete than that, but it is an area of interest, especially as we're trying to consider how do you have a human rights framework in municipal governance?

250
00:26:11,285 --> 00:26:18,811
[SPEAKER_05]: How do you have human rights values and principles at the forefront when evaluating things that are proposed before the city council?

251
00:26:19,614 --> 00:26:26,540
[SPEAKER_05]: things that are before the planning board and zoning, environmental justice and health equity, these things that touch on these different departments.

252
00:26:26,860 --> 00:26:43,775
[SPEAKER_05]: How can you bring those departments in so that they're doing some of this work and it's not always the human rights commission, but maybe the human rights commission is sort of overseeing some of that or keeping everybody on the same page or helping provide resources to some of these different

253
00:26:44,673 --> 00:26:53,175
[SPEAKER_05]: departments so that they can do that and really implement these principles and practices in every department with every employee.

254
00:26:54,495 --> 00:27:06,738
[SPEAKER_05]: So that no matter how residents or guests to the town interface with the town, they're getting that human rights component considered.

255
00:27:06,758 --> 00:27:12,320
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

256
00:27:16,443 --> 00:27:19,055
[SPEAKER_08]: Any other questions from our commissioners for Adam?

257
00:27:24,570 --> 00:27:30,032
[SPEAKER_09]: Hey, Adam, I have one question based on what you were just talking about with the advisory body.

258
00:27:30,232 --> 00:27:46,338
[SPEAKER_09]: Who are your strategic partners or groups that really do want to come in at the coalition at the state level and have those conversations and want to be active participants with you all as well?

259
00:27:48,439 --> 00:27:49,139
[SPEAKER_05]: Who are our partners?

260
00:27:49,859 --> 00:27:50,080
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

261
00:27:52,312 --> 00:27:53,533
[SPEAKER_05]: It's varied and growing.

262
00:27:54,313 --> 00:27:57,295
[SPEAKER_05]: Primarily, it's been other human rights committees.

263
00:27:57,875 --> 00:28:03,019
[SPEAKER_05]: There's been a number of nonprofits that have sort of a similar broad scope to their mission.

264
00:28:03,039 --> 00:28:04,720
[SPEAKER_05]: Excuse me.

265
00:28:04,800 --> 00:28:10,924
[SPEAKER_05]: But we also have relationships with the Department of Justice and folks in the US Attorney's Office.

266
00:28:12,464 --> 00:28:20,209
[SPEAKER_05]: District attorneys participate from time to time or will join some of their anti-bias events that they put on.

267
00:28:22,971 --> 00:28:26,753
[SPEAKER_05]: I think that's primarily it for the most part at this point.

268
00:28:26,933 --> 00:28:30,495
[SPEAKER_05]: But different commissions have different relationships with the stakeholders in their towns.

269
00:28:30,735 --> 00:28:33,957
[SPEAKER_05]: I know Boston is building relationships with DOJ and others.

270
00:28:34,718 --> 00:28:43,582
[SPEAKER_05]: I know Melrose, they're building relationships not only with the departments in the city, but with the hospital and other relevant stakeholders.

271
00:28:44,123 --> 00:28:51,607
[SPEAKER_05]: It kind of depends on where everyone is, but as far as

272
00:28:53,376 --> 00:28:55,017
[SPEAKER_05]: sort of our official relationship.

273
00:28:55,538 --> 00:28:58,300
[SPEAKER_05]: We don't have an official relationship with the state.

274
00:28:58,540 --> 00:29:09,370
[SPEAKER_05]: We are an unincorporated association of members of human rights commissions, who each of us have different relationships with different people at different parts of the state.

275
00:29:10,010 --> 00:29:17,576
[SPEAKER_05]: So for example, we do a lot of work with Senator Lewis, Jason Lewis from Winchester, who

276
00:29:19,220 --> 00:29:22,682
[SPEAKER_05]: is I'm in his district, but he's done a lot of work in this area.

277
00:29:23,223 --> 00:29:25,684
[SPEAKER_05]: And so we've had a lot of overlap with his office.

278
00:29:25,724 --> 00:29:28,546
[SPEAKER_05]: He's been supportive of this and what we do.

279
00:29:30,247 --> 00:29:31,348
[SPEAKER_05]: But I hope that answered the question.

280
00:29:31,929 --> 00:29:32,449
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah, it did.

281
00:29:32,549 --> 00:29:33,189
[SPEAKER_09]: No, thank you.

282
00:29:33,430 --> 00:29:33,830
[SPEAKER_09]: That was helpful.

283
00:29:33,850 --> 00:29:34,050
[SPEAKER_09]: Thanks.

284
00:29:34,090 --> 00:29:38,333
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you so much, Adam.

285
00:29:39,333 --> 00:29:47,339
[SPEAKER_08]: Chief and Rob, do you have any questions for Adam before I turn it over to public participation?

286
00:29:48,613 --> 00:29:56,355
[SPEAKER_11]: I was just fascinated by a little bit of the origins of the Medford Human Rights Commission, because I don't think even I had that depth of knowledge of it.

287
00:29:56,395 --> 00:30:00,096
[SPEAKER_11]: So it was good to hear and kind of reinforce what we're trying to do here.

288
00:30:00,236 --> 00:30:05,778
[SPEAKER_11]: I mean, he may or may not be aware of the struggles we've had over the last couple of years trying to get our own identity.

289
00:30:06,779 --> 00:30:17,070
[SPEAKER_11]: I guess it's probably appropriate for me to ask, as you mentioned earlier, is the relationship with police and was that relationship with police as it relates to Human Rights Commission and their participation on the Human Rights Commissions?

290
00:30:17,871 --> 00:30:18,832
[SPEAKER_11]: Is that a common thing?

291
00:30:18,852 --> 00:30:24,619
[SPEAKER_11]: Because I've sat in that, my predecessor, Chief Sacco, sat on the Human Rights Commission for many years prior to that.

292
00:30:24,639 --> 00:30:27,202
[SPEAKER_11]: I'm just wondering what your thoughts are as it relates to that.

293
00:30:28,512 --> 00:30:29,173
[SPEAKER_05]: It's a little bit of both.

294
00:30:29,593 --> 00:30:39,181
[SPEAKER_05]: And several HRCs do have a role for, it's either the chief who is liaison or someone designated by the chief.

295
00:30:39,561 --> 00:30:41,442
[SPEAKER_05]: Otherwise, it was just a close relationship.

296
00:30:41,502 --> 00:30:49,829
[SPEAKER_05]: We would, Chief Lyle was chief when I was on the commission, and so we would have a pretty close relationship with Chief Lyle and try to coordinate on events.

297
00:30:51,350 --> 00:30:55,273
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think one of the topics we are always trying to address is,

298
00:30:57,085 --> 00:31:07,478
[SPEAKER_05]: how to resolve issues of trust that are experienced in the community and build relationships with law enforcement so that folks can

299
00:31:10,208 --> 00:31:13,953
[SPEAKER_05]: feel more confident in reaching out and comfortable reaching out as needed.

300
00:31:14,273 --> 00:31:17,216
[SPEAKER_05]: And law enforcement can feel more comfortable in doing what they need to do.

301
00:31:18,358 --> 00:31:21,942
[SPEAKER_05]: We had a convening on this about four years ago.

302
00:31:22,383 --> 00:31:29,591
[SPEAKER_05]: And Chief Ryan from Arlington really talked about the role that can be played

303
00:31:31,035 --> 00:31:33,816
[SPEAKER_05]: at this intersection with law enforcement, by law enforcement.

304
00:31:34,157 --> 00:31:41,881
[SPEAKER_11]: Yeah, as I said, this is, I'm starting my 60th now, and I think we've really tried to do that in the city here.

305
00:31:41,961 --> 00:31:53,186
[SPEAKER_11]: But, you know, it's a continual effort, because in some sense, you're never going to know where your impact, you know, is and which communities you may not be reaching and which communities may still hold some sort of trust issues.

306
00:31:53,266 --> 00:31:54,907
[SPEAKER_11]: And, you know, especially with our

307
00:31:56,748 --> 00:32:00,231
[SPEAKER_11]: you know, more of a migrant or immigrant community is coming in.

308
00:32:00,352 --> 00:32:01,973
[SPEAKER_11]: So we continue to work on that.

309
00:32:02,013 --> 00:32:05,376
[SPEAKER_11]: And I'm glad the Human Rights Commission can be part of that and have those discussions with us.

310
00:32:05,396 --> 00:32:06,477
[SPEAKER_11]: So thanks.

311
00:32:06,998 --> 00:32:09,480
[SPEAKER_05]: And yet another way to have to build relationships.

312
00:32:09,700 --> 00:32:17,688
[SPEAKER_05]: And if there's someone on the commission, or someone on the commission knows someone who could be a liaison, if there was ever a need, you know, that network exists.

313
00:32:18,168 --> 00:32:18,368
[SPEAKER_11]: Yeah.

314
00:32:18,989 --> 00:32:19,790
[SPEAKER_11]: Yeah, valid point.

315
00:32:19,930 --> 00:32:20,070
[SPEAKER_11]: Good.

316
00:32:22,768 --> 00:32:24,008
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Chief.

317
00:32:24,548 --> 00:32:28,309
[SPEAKER_08]: Rob, I don't know if you had any questions for Adam.

318
00:32:29,309 --> 00:32:30,509
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, just very quickly.

319
00:32:30,569 --> 00:32:32,350
[SPEAKER_01]: First, thanks very much, Adam, for participating.

320
00:32:32,370 --> 00:32:39,151
[SPEAKER_01]: This has been really enlightening and reinforcing to hear that these types of things are going on all throughout the Commonwealth.

321
00:32:39,911 --> 00:32:51,793
[SPEAKER_01]: You mentioned a little while ago that you spent some time really digging in and compiling quite a bit of information about where there are other committees, commissions, you know, what have you, however they're termed in specific communities.

322
00:32:52,694 --> 00:33:06,804
[SPEAKER_01]: I would love to see any consolidated documentation you have about what those different groups take on or, you know, how they organize themselves, kind of assuming that you put together something formal and consolidated.

323
00:33:06,824 --> 00:33:09,306
[SPEAKER_01]: So, if you have that, it would be great if you're comfortable to share it.

324
00:33:10,146 --> 00:33:10,367
[SPEAKER_01]: Sure.

325
00:33:10,567 --> 00:33:14,770
[SPEAKER_05]: I'll put in the chat right here, if I can find it.

326
00:33:14,830 --> 00:33:17,032
[SPEAKER_05]: Is that an option?

327
00:33:17,112 --> 00:33:17,452
[SPEAKER_05]: There it is.

328
00:33:19,087 --> 00:33:24,210
[SPEAKER_05]: just a link to some of our public facing resources that are available on our website.

329
00:33:25,790 --> 00:33:34,794
[SPEAKER_05]: I don't believe it has that spreadsheet that we put together with the different human rights groups.

330
00:33:36,495 --> 00:33:37,175
[SPEAKER_05]: But let's see.

331
00:33:39,076 --> 00:33:43,598
[SPEAKER_05]: But I would be happy to talk further or talk offline more about that.

332
00:33:43,658 --> 00:33:44,358
[SPEAKER_05]: We do have that.

333
00:33:45,199 --> 00:33:47,700
[SPEAKER_05]: Actually, it probably needs to be updated a little bit because it's been about a year.

334
00:33:48,435 --> 00:33:55,777
[SPEAKER_05]: But I'm aware now that there are a few more groups, including Watertown, that should be updated on there.

335
00:33:57,817 --> 00:33:58,077
[SPEAKER_05]: Great.

336
00:33:58,397 --> 00:33:58,757
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

337
00:34:00,938 --> 00:34:01,338
[SPEAKER_08]: All right.

338
00:34:01,498 --> 00:34:03,118
[SPEAKER_08]: Thanks, Adam.

339
00:34:04,379 --> 00:34:07,900
[SPEAKER_08]: I'll email the link to all the commissioners.

340
00:34:08,580 --> 00:34:08,960
[SPEAKER_08]: All right.

341
00:34:09,040 --> 00:34:15,081
[SPEAKER_08]: So at this point, I'm going to turn it to our two guests that I see in case they have any questions for Adam.

342
00:34:16,041 --> 00:34:18,022
[SPEAKER_08]: Steve, do you have any questions for Adam?

343
00:34:19,074 --> 00:34:20,135
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes, thanks, Francis.

344
00:34:20,615 --> 00:34:21,515
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm just curious.

345
00:34:22,236 --> 00:34:33,622
[SPEAKER_10]: I believe you briefly mentioned Boston or another HRC that was dealing with or made a statement about Israel-Palestine.

346
00:34:34,882 --> 00:34:37,946
[SPEAKER_10]: And I just quickly went to your website.

347
00:34:38,066 --> 00:34:41,850
[SPEAKER_10]: I didn't see anything about that on your website.

348
00:34:42,431 --> 00:34:49,098
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm just curious as to what you have heard about HRCs in relation to Israel-Palestine.

349
00:34:51,073 --> 00:34:54,534
[SPEAKER_05]: At this point, it's the statements, some of which are in that folder.

350
00:34:55,294 --> 00:34:58,535
[SPEAKER_05]: You'll see examples of statements that have been issued by different groups publicly.

351
00:34:59,495 --> 00:35:02,176
[SPEAKER_05]: Boston's is not in there yet, though I'm aware that they did publish one.

352
00:35:02,696 --> 00:35:05,797
[SPEAKER_05]: And I've asked if they would like us to include it in that list.

353
00:35:06,237 --> 00:35:07,818
[SPEAKER_05]: I haven't heard back yet.

354
00:35:08,578 --> 00:35:11,879
[SPEAKER_05]: But if they're agreeable, we'll add that to the list as well.

355
00:35:13,139 --> 00:35:13,559
[SPEAKER_05]: How many?

356
00:35:13,619 --> 00:35:14,400
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm just curious.

357
00:35:15,500 --> 00:35:19,481
[SPEAKER_05]: I believe there are five so far that agreed to have theirs shared here.

358
00:35:20,791 --> 00:35:24,912
[SPEAKER_05]: I think there were probably eight or ten that I'm aware of who have issued statements.

359
00:35:27,172 --> 00:35:28,413
[SPEAKER_05]: Not all of them were written.

360
00:35:28,553 --> 00:35:31,593
[SPEAKER_05]: Some were videos that were posted on their social media.

361
00:35:32,793 --> 00:35:35,514
[SPEAKER_05]: So the ones that we have are examples of written statements.

362
00:35:37,374 --> 00:35:37,714
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

363
00:35:37,754 --> 00:35:38,554
[SPEAKER_10]: That's very helpful.

