689
01:05:19,036 --> 01:05:23,879
[SPEAKER_08]: It's the annual reading of the Belinda Sutton petition.

690
01:05:26,448 --> 01:05:42,296
[SPEAKER_08]: Maureen and Steph, I don't think that you were a part of this last year, but this is something that the Human Rights Commission had put together, and it took place at the Royal House and Slave Quarters.

691
01:05:43,297 --> 01:05:49,921
[SPEAKER_08]: And when I say there was standing room only, there literally was just standing room only.

692
01:05:50,461 --> 01:05:51,721
[SPEAKER_08]: I think we ran out of chairs.

693
01:05:52,891 --> 01:05:54,652
[SPEAKER_08]: And there was no space to put the chairs.

694
01:05:55,052 --> 01:05:59,435
[SPEAKER_08]: So people really enjoyed it.

695
01:06:00,595 --> 01:06:14,083
[SPEAKER_08]: We had the group Tufts S Factor from Tufts University perform in the Africana style of a cappella music, which is very moving.

696
01:06:15,123 --> 01:06:17,765
[SPEAKER_08]: Very, very different to like gospel sounds.

697
01:06:18,325 --> 01:06:21,166
[SPEAKER_08]: If you've heard the original

698
01:06:22,367 --> 01:06:26,629
[SPEAKER_08]: like Mahalia Jackson style of Wade in the Water.

699
01:06:26,669 --> 01:06:28,830
[SPEAKER_08]: It's almost like the cry of the soul.

700
01:06:28,850 --> 01:06:35,833
[SPEAKER_08]: I don't know if anybody else has a different way of explaining that sound of music.

701
01:06:37,014 --> 01:06:39,275
[SPEAKER_08]: But it was great.

702
01:06:40,055 --> 01:06:48,179
[SPEAKER_08]: I mean, it ended up snowing and people still came out and I didn't hear anything negative.

703
01:06:49,580 --> 01:06:54,668
[SPEAKER_08]: about the event and people enjoyed a tour after the event.

704
01:06:57,085 --> 01:07:05,391
[SPEAKER_08]: It's been proposed that we keep this up because the first one was just so moving and so well attended.

705
01:07:05,891 --> 01:07:21,762
[SPEAKER_08]: But why deviate from this if we can continue to expand and expose Belinda Sutton, the meaning behind Belinda Sutton's writings, the meaning behind Belinda Sutton's work.

706
